<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="yes"?>
<bug>
    <id>4794</id>
    <title>Magic Link: Some emails linked to WordPress.com accounts aren't recognized</title>
    <description>
        <paragraph id="1">
            <sentence id="1.1">### Expected behavior</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="2">
            <sentence id="2.1">I expect that if I enter an email address linked to a WordPress.com account in the login form, I will proceed through the magic link login flow.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="3">
            <sentence id="3.1">### Actual behavior</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="4">
            <sentence id="4.1">Some email addresses are not recognized as being linked to a WordPress.com account, so after entering the email address I am taken to the self-hosted login form.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="5">
            <sentence id="5.1">Tapping "Log in to WordPress.com" takes me back to the previous login form (username/email only), but I still can't force a WordPress.com login â€” when I try to go to the next screen I am taken again to the self-hosted login form.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="6">
            <sentence id="6.1">I noticed that this seemed to consistently happen with Gmail addresses using + addressing, e.g. 'example+wordpress@gmail.com'.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="7">
            <sentence id="7.1">### Steps to reproduce the behavior</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="8">
            <sentence id="8.1">1 Open the app (logged out) on the WordPress.com login screen</sentence>
            <sentence id="8.2">2 Enter a Gmail address with + addressing linked to a WordPress.com account</sentence>
            <sentence id="8.3">3 Tap the "Next" button</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="9">
            <sentence id="9.1">Result: The form takes you to the self-hosted login form, even though the email is linked to a WordPress.com account.</sentence>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph id="10">
            <sentence id="10.1">##### Tested on Nexus 9, Android 7.0, WPAndroid alpha-28</sentence>
        </paragraph>
    </description>
</bug>
